Yes, absolutely! The minimal approach is much simpler. You only touch 2 files (config.py and main.py) and make one small fix in each page file. Here's exactly what to do:

Step 1 — config.py — Add 2 things (nothing else changes)
Add the MODEL_REGISTRY dict and a set_model() function at the bottom of your existing config.py. Don't change anything else.
python# ── Paste this at the BOTTOM of your existing config.py ──────────────────

MODEL_REGISTRY = {
    "S26U": {"base": "S25U", "n": 89},
    "A37":  {"base": "A36",  "n": 59},
    "A57":  {"base": "A56",  "n": 60},
}

def set_model(selected_model: str):
    """Call this from main.py whenever the selectbox changes."""
    global main, base, n, base_dir
    global file_path, comparison_path_overall, comparison_path_domestic
    global comparison_path_export, file_base_path, asrdata_path, marketing_name

    entry    = MODEL_REGISTRY[selected_model]
    main     = selected_model
    base     = entry["base"]
    n        = entry["n"]
    base_dir = rf".\{main} Data\{n}days"

    file_path                  = rf"{base_dir}\raw_main.xlsx"
    comparison_path_overall    = rf"{base_dir}\overall.xlsx"
    comparison_path_domestic   = rf"{base_dir}\domestic.xlsx"
    comparison_path_export     = rf"{base_dir}\export.xlsx"
    file_base_path             = rf"{base_dir}\raw_base.xlsx"
    asrdata_path               = rf"{base_dir}\asr_compare.xlsx"
    marketing_name             = f"Galaxy {main}"

Step 2 — main.py — Add selectbox + call set_model()
Find where you import config and where you render the FDM header. Add these 4 lines:
pythonimport config  # make sure you import as module, not just "from config import ..."
from config import MODEL_REGISTRY

# ── Add this BEFORE the FDM header render ────────────────────────────────

selected_model = st.selectbox(
    "Select Model",
    options=list(MODEL_REGISTRY.keys()),   # ["S26U", "A37", "A57"]
    key="model_picker",
)
config.set_model(selected_model)           # ← this updates ALL paths in config
That's it for main.py. Now config.main, config.base, config.file_path etc. are all updated before any page loads.

Step 3 — Each page file (summary.py, analysis.py, improvement.py)
Only 2 things to fix per page file:
Fix 1 — Cache bust (so switching model actually loads new data)
python# BEFORE
@st.cache_data
def load_data():
    return get_data()

df = load_data()

# AFTER — add model as parameter so cache refreshes on switch
@st.cache_data
def load_data(model):        # ← model string is the cache key
    return get_data()

df = load_data(config.main)  # ← pass current model
Fix 2 — Labels/titles that use main or base
If you have anything like f"{main} vs {base}" in a chart title or heading, change it to read from the module:
python# BEFORE
st.markdown(f"{main} Model Comparison")

# AFTER
import config
st.markdown(f"{config.main} Model Comparison")

Why? When Python does from config import main, it copies the string value once at startup. config.main always reads the live current value.


Why this works
selectbox changes
      ↓
config.set_model("A37")  ← updates all global vars in config module
      ↓
page's get_data() runs   ← reads config.file_path which is now A37's path ✓
page's cache key changes ← "A37" ≠ "S26U", so cache loads fresh data ✓
page's config.main label ← reads live value "A37" ✓
The data-loading functions (get_data, get_overall_comparison_data, etc.) already read from config's module-level globals at call time — so they update automatically. The only manual fixes are the cache key and any string labels.

To add a 4th model in the future, just add one line to MODEL_REGISTRY in config.py:
python"S25U": {"base": "S24U", "n": 75},
